Introduction

Photo by Pang Yuhao on Unsplash

The first step in the process of turning information into knowledge is to summarize and describe the raw information - the data. In this assignment, we explore data on college majors and earnings, specifically the data behind the FiveThirtyEight story The Economic Guide To Picking A College Major.

These data originally come from the American Community Survey (ACS) 2010-2012 Public Use Microdata Series. While this is outside the scope of this assignment, if you are curious about how raw data from the ACS were cleaned and prepared, see the code FiveThirtyEight authors used.

We should also note that there are many considerations that go into picking a major. Earnings potential and employment prospects are two of them, and they are important, but they do not tell the whole story. Keep this in mind as you analyze the data.

Majors and unemployment rate

In order to see which majors have the lowest unemployment rate, all we need to do is sort the data. We use the arrange() function to do this, and sort it by the unemployment_rate variable. By default, arrange sorts from smallest to largest, which is what we want here – we’re interested in the major with the lowest unemployment rate.

Majors and median income

There are three types of incomes reported in this data frame: p25th, median, and p75th. These correspond to the 25th, 50th, and 75th percentiles of the income distribution of sampled individuals for a given major.

We begin by comparing incomes within a single major category.

We need to do a few things to answer the question of how incomes compare across major categories. First, we need to group the data by major_category. Then we need to average across the incomes within a category.

The group_by function in dplyr establishes groups based on the variable we specify. The summarize function when used after a group_by will calculate summaries for each one separately.

For instance, the following code calculates the average (or mean) of the median income for each major category. Recall that it is good practice to specify how missing values should be treated when using the mean.

college_recent_grads %>% 
  group_by(major_category) %>%
  summarize( avg_income = mean(median, na.rm=TRUE) )
## # A tibble: 16 × 2

Note from the output that group_by followed by the summarize function creates a smaller data frame containing just two variables: the grouping variable major_category and the summary you wish to calculate avg_income. The name of the summary variable is specified by you, the user. The name is optional but helpful especially if you want to pipe the result to arrange to sort in order.

Summary statistics: Some useful function calls for summary statistics for a single numerical variable are as follows. Each takes a single column of data as an argument and returns a single value.

  • sum: sum
  • mean: average
  • median: median
  • sd: standard deviation
  • var: variance
  • IQR: interquartile range (range of middle 50%)
  • min: minimum
  • max: maximum

Together, group_by and summarize open up a lot of possibilities for calculating interesting summaries of the data. We will use them a lot in subsequent labs and homework!
